  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a), you need to follow these steps:\n\n1. Identify the components:\n- Nitrogen (N)\n- Hydrogen (H)\n\n2. Find the atomic masses:\n- Nitrogen: 14.0 g/mol\n- Hydrogen: 1.0 g/mol\n\n3. Calculate the molecular mass:\n- 1 Nitrogen atom: 14.0 g/mol\n- 4 Hydrogen atoms: 4 \u00d7 1.0 = 4.0 g/mol\n- Total molecular mass: 14.0 + 4.0 = 18.0 g/mol\n\n4. Note: In the ammonium ion, one hydrogen atom has an extra electron, creating a positive charge, but this does not change the molecular mass calculation.\n\nSo, the molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a) is 18.0 g/mol.\n\nRemember that molecular mass represents the sum of the atomic masses of all atoms in a molecule or ion.",
